message_1:
If we have the following system of equations:

\begin{align*}
3x-2y&=7 \\
6x-4y&=14 \\
\end{align*}

Determine whether this system of linear equations has a solution or not.

message_2:
To determine whether this system of linear equations has a solution or not, we can first check if the equations are multiples of each other.

Divide the second equation by 2:

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}(6x-4y) &= \frac{1}{2}(14) \\
3x-2y &= 7 \\
\end{align*}

We can see that the two equations are the same:

\begin{align*}
3x-2y&=7 \\
3x-2y&=7 \\
\end{align*}

Since both equations are the same, they represent the same line. Therefore, this system of linear equations has infinitely many solutions, as every point on the line is a solution.
